Here's a comprehensive prompt that captures everything we built:

White-Label Component (WLC) Integration with Camunda 8.7 On-Premises
Build a White-Label Component (WLC) that integrates with a Camunda 8.7 on-premises workflow engine. The WLC acts as the user-facing layer for any Camunda process — it renders dynamic forms, routes submitted data, and advances the workflow — while keeping its own business data completely isolated from Camunda's internal datastore.

Core Architecture
The system has two independent data domains that must never share a datastore. The WLC domain owns a PostgreSQL database storing workflow definitions, JSON form templates, business data submitted by users, and an append-only audit log. The Camunda domain owns its internal Elasticsearch and RocksDB stores containing process variables, instance state, and task history. The only connection between the two domains is a narrow API bridge consisting of exactly three REST calls made by the WLC Schema Service to the Camunda REST Gateway.

Dynamic Form Engine
The WLC must render user interfaces dynamically from JSON templates stored in its own database — no hardcoded forms. Each JSON template describes a step in a Camunda workflow and contains a schema array of field definitions. Each field has an id, type (text, email, number, date, select, textarea, checkbox), label, required flag, and a critical camundaVar boolean. Fields marked camundaVar: true are process variables that drive Camunda gateway decisions; fields marked camundaVar: false are business data that belongs only to the WLC. The renderer must support conditional field visibility via a showWhen property that shows a field only when another field has a specific value.

Data Routing
When a user submits a form, the WLC must split the payload on the camundaVar flag before persisting anything. Fields with camundaVar: true are sent to Camunda via POST /v1/tasks/:taskId/complete as process variables. Fields with camundaVar: false are written to the WLC PostgreSQL database in the step_submissions.wlc_data JSONB column. This split must happen in a single database transaction so that partial writes are impossible. Camunda must never receive WLC business fields, and the WLC database must never store Camunda process variables as a source of truth.

Workflow Lifecycle
When a user initiates a process, the WLC calls POST /v1/process-instances on Camunda and registers the resulting instance key in its own process_instances table. After each step submission, the WLC polls GET /v1/user-tasks?processInstanceKey=… to ask Camunda what the next user task is. Camunda returns a taskDefinitionId which the WLC uses as a key to look up the next JSON form template from its own database. This lookup-submit-poll cycle repeats until the Camunda process reaches an end event.

Alert Investigation Workflow
The reference implementation is a three-level SOC alert investigation process: L1 Alert Analysis → L2 Alert Analysis → QA Analysis. Each level has a specific set of available actions controlled by the availableActions array in the JSON template. L1 can ESCALATE (to L2) or CLOSE (end the investigation). L2 can ESCALATE (to QA), CLOSE, or SEND_BACK (to L1 to request more information). QA can CLOSE (triggering a compliance notification check) or SEND_BACK (to L2 for rework). The SEND_BACK paths are implemented as loop-back sequence flows in the BPMN — the Camunda token re-enters the previous user task natively. The BPMN uses exclusive (XOR) gateways with FEEL expressions that evaluate the action process variable submitted by the WLC.

Database Schema
The WLC PostgreSQL database requires five tables. camunda_workflows is the registry of Camunda process definition keys and their display metadata. workflow_steps stores the JSON form template for each user task, keyed by workflow_id and camunda_step_id, with the template stored as a JSONB column with a GIN index. process_instances tracks runtime state including the current step and active Camunda task ID. step_submissions is an immutable record of every form submission, storing wlc_data (business fields) and camunda_variables (audit mirror of what was sent to Camunda) as separate JSONB columns. wlc_audit_log is an append-only table protected by PostgreSQL rules that block UPDATE and DELETE, recording every process event with an audit_event_type enum and a log_audit_event() stored function for consistent inserts.

Backend API
The WLC exposes a Node.js Express REST API on port 3001. The hottest endpoint is GET /api/workflows/:processKey/steps/:stepId/template which the frontend calls after receiving a taskDefinitionId from Camunda. Admin endpoints (PUT /api/admin/workflows/:key/steps/:stepId) allow new workflows and form templates to be registered without code changes. All SQL is defined as named query constants in a single file — no inline SQL in business logic. All cross-step submissions execute inside a PostgreSQL transaction that atomically writes the WLC data, updates the instance state, and inserts the audit event.

Frontend
Provide both a React 18 implementation and an Angular 17 implementation. In React, use a useWorkflowEngine custom hook to manage all workflow state and a renderField() function that switches on field.type to produce the appropriate HTML element. In Angular, replace the hook with two injectable services — SchemaService for schema fetching and payload splitting, and WorkflowStateService using Angular 17 Signals for reactive state. Replace renderField() with a DynamicFieldComponent that accepts a FormField and a FormControl as inputs. Use ReactiveFormsModule with a FormGroup built programmatically from the JSON schema. The Angular template uses *ngFor over the schema array and *ngIf for conditional fields.

Constraints and Non-Negotiables
The WLC database and Camunda database must be fully isolated — no shared tables, no direct cross-database queries, no ETL between them. The only data that crosses the boundary is what passes through the three defined REST calls. New workflows must be addable by inserting rows into the database and uploading a BPMN file — no frontend or backend code changes required. Every user action must produce an immutable audit log entry. The compliance notification after QA closure must be implemented as a Zeebe job worker consuming a compliance-notify service task, not as direct code in the WLC submission path.
